{"attack":true,"case":"The proposal violates std-crit-design clause (2) via a sample-size honesty gap that makes its forbidden cases unmeasurable as stated. Forbidden case #3 is: 'Experiment shows harness > SC by >= 0.03 at P(fragile) = 0.1 with critic precision-on-fragile = 0.4.' Yet the proposal's own final design (in prose_notes) scales to 20 questions x 2 tiers = 40 questions total. At P(fragile)=0.1 in the mid-error tier, only ~2 fragile questions are expected (10 questions x 0.1). A >=0.03 accuracy gap on a 10-question tier requires >=0.3 net correct, i.e. a single question flip. On fragile questions specifically, with n_fragile≈2, a single flip changes per-question fragile accuracy by 0.5 — so the >=0.03 threshold is trivially triggered by noise, not a refuting signal. Conversely, the proposal's own explanation of the v4-flash 0/0 result concedes that at P(fragile)=0.04, a net effect of -0.014 is 'indistinguishable from 0 at n=24.' The proposed design has fewer questions per tier (10) than that baseline (24) and targets a smaller effect (0.03 vs 0.014), so the threshold is even less distinguishable from zero. Forbidden case #2 (harness < SC by >=0.05 at P(fragile)=0.2) is likewise underpowered: at P(fragile)=0.2, ~2 fragile questions are expected, and >=0.05 accuracy on 10 questions = 0.5 net correct = one flip, again noise-level. The forbidden cases cannot be measured by rerunning this repository's validation harness at the proposed scale because the harness cannot distinguish the specified thresholds from sampling noise, violating the measurability requirement of clause (2).","counterexample":null}